04485nam a22006255i 9780292745872DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927458727 a10.7560/7458652doi  a(DE-B1597)587212  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a792.709621 avan Nieuwkerk, Karin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerforming Piety :bSingers and Actors in Egypt's Islamic Revival /cKarin van Nieuwkerk. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. The 1980s -- tCelebrating Piety -- tChapter one. Dreams, Spirituality, and the Piety Movement -- tChapter two. Repentance, Daʿwah, and Religious Education -- tChapter three. Veiling and Charity -- tPart Two. The 1990s -- tDebating Religion, Gender, and the Performing Arts in the Public Sphere -- tChapter four. The Islamist (Counter)public -- tChapter five. The Secular Cultural Field -- tChapter six. Changing Discourses on Art and Gender -- tPart Three. The New Millennium -- tPerforming Piety -- tChapter seven. Art with a Mission and Post-Islamism -- tChapter eight. Halal Weddings and Religious Markets -- tChapter nine. Ramadan Soaps and Islamic Aesthetics -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1980s, Egypt witnessed a growing revival of religiosity among large sectors of the population, including artists. Many pious stars retired from art, “repented” from “sinful” activities, and dedicated themselves to worship, preaching, and charity. Their public conversions were influential in spreading piety to the Egyptian upper class during the 1990s, which in turn enabled the development of pious markets for leisure and art, thus facilitating the return of artists as veiled actresses or religiously committed performers. Revisiting the story she began in “A Trade like Any Other”: Female Singers and Dancers in Egypt, Karin van Nieuwkerk draws on extensive fieldwork among performers to offer a unique history of the religious revival in Egypt through the lens of the performing arts. She highlights the narratives of celebrities who retired in the 1980s and early 1990s, including their spiritual journeys and their influence on the “pietization” of their fans, among whom are the wealthy, relatively secular, strata of Egyptian society. Van Nieuwkerk then turns to the emergence of a polemic public sphere in which secularists and Islamists debated Islam, art, and gender in the 1990s. Finally, she analyzes the Islamist project of “art with a mission” and the development of Islamic aesthetics, questioning whether the outcome has been to Islamize popular art or rather to popularize Islam. The result is an intimate thirty-year history of two spheres that have tremendous importance for Egypt—art production and piety.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEntertainersxReligious lifezEgypt. 0aEntertainerszEgyptvBiography. 0aIslamic renewalzEgypt. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74586540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292745872423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292745872/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK